17_15	0.089039356	Since 1939, 11 quakes have occurred at sites along the North Anatolian Fault that are almost always progressively farther to the west with each occurrence, ``like falling dominoes,'' as the scientists described it.
17_16	0.095202637	The quake sequence along the North Anatolian Fault zone is unusual in that no other fault zones on Earth show such a neat, domino-style pattern of occurrence.
17_17	0.11202848	According to geological theory, a quake changes crustal stress in a region and might increase the possibility of a future quake in that region.
17_18	0.14456342	According to the calculations by the scientists, a 1967 quake immediately to the east of Izmit increased stress in that region.
17_19	0.10897253	In the paper, they forecast that the increased stress could eventually cause a major quake on the Sapanca Fault.
17_20	0.091605029	On this basis, the three scientists proposed in their article that over the next 30 years, there was a 12 percent probability for a large event south of Izmit, which lies farther west than the 1967 quake.
